@node Overview "Overview"

This is a conversion of the 1977 3W board game "Africa", for up to 5
players. Players can be controlled by human or Amiga.

In this game each player takes the role of one of the powers attempting to
establish or maintain a sphere of influence in the southern half of the
African continent. By interfering in the economic stability and political
alliances of nations, and by subsidising them, the players attempt to
extend their political control of Africa, while diminishing the control of
their opponents.

There is the opportunity to set up governments in favour of the players,
encourage revolutions, start wars between the African nations and even
introduce armies of the player-powers into the continent.

Source code is included. The supported languages are currently English,
German, Greek and Italian.
@endnode

@node Requirements "System Requirements"

@{b}Hardware@{ub}             Required       640x512x64 capability
                                     (AGA/RTG)  (OS3)
                                     (RTG only) (OS4)
                                    about 2½Mb free RAM
                     Recommended    Flixer fixer
                                    Keyboard with numeric keypad
@{b}Firmware@{ub}             Required       Kickstart R3.0+
@{b}Software@{ub}             Required       OS3.0+
                     Recommended    OpenURL.library
                                    TCP/IP stack

The user's preferred screen mode, game mode, etc. are stored in the
Africa.config file.

If the Africa.config file does not exist, you will be asked to select
your preferred screen mode. You need at least 640*512 resolution in 64
colours. There is no benefit in selecting more colours than this.

The OS3 version is not intended for OS4 nor MorphOS, and compatibility of
it with those platforms is not assured. You should run the native port for
your platform (because some of the compatibility logic is done at compile-
time rather than at runtime).

If the CLI argument or Workbench tooltype PUBSCREEN is specified, the
game will use the named public screen. This public screen should be at
least slightly larger than 640x512 for this (to accommodate the window
borders.)
  The game allocates various pens if run on a public screen. If there are
not enough available pens, some countries may be shown in grey.
@endnode

@node Arguments "Startup Arguments"

@{b}CLI Arguments@{ub}

                                   @{b}Africa@{ub}

@{b}Format:          Africa@{ub}
                      [USA=HUMAN|AMIGA]
                     [USSR=HUMAN|AMIGA]
                    [CHINA=HUMAN|AMIGA]
                   [FRANCE=HUMAN|AMIGA]
                       [UK=HUMAN|AMIGA]
                 [SCREENMODE]
                 [PUBSCREEN=<@{i}screenname@{ui}>]
                    [[FILE=]<@{i}savedgame@{ui}>]]

@{b}Template:@{ub}        USA/K,USSR/K,CHINA/K,FRANCE/K,UK/K,SCREENMODE/S,
                 PUBSCREEN/K,FILE

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}         To run the Africa game.

@{b}Specification:@{ub}

    <player>:    Controls for the relevant player. This will override
                 the relevant value stored in Africa.config.

    SCREENMODE:  This allows you to choose a new screenmode at startup,
                 even if an Africa.config file exists.

    PUBSCREEN:   Name of the public screen to run the game on.

    <@{i}savedgame@{ui}>:  The pathname of your saved game to load at
                 startup. This is taken exactly as entered; an '@{b}.africa@{ub}'
                 extension is not automatically appended.

    ?:           Displays the command line argument format.

The order of the arguments is interchangeable.

@{b}Workbench ToolTypes@{ub}

        USA=HUMAN|AMIGA                   eg. USA=HUMAN
       USSR=HUMAN|AMIGA
      CHINA=HUMAN|AMIGA
     FRANCE=HUMAN|AMIGA
         UK=HUMAN|AMIGA
 SCREENMODE                               eg. SCREENMODE
  PUBSCREEN=<screenname>                  eg. PUBSCREEN=Workbench
       FILE=<savedgame>                   eg. FILE=foo.africa

These are equivalent to the relevant CLI arguments.

If you double-click on a saved game file, the game will load with that
saved game. In that case, ToolTypes are of course, taken from the saved
game's .info file.

@{b}How to Run Africa in Greek@{ub}

You need to be using an appropriate 8-point monospaced Greek font (ie. one
which is designed for code page ELOT 928). There are several such fonts
available, eg. from http://www.hri.org/culture97/fonts/AmiGR.lha . Copy
one or all of them into FONTS: . You should download and install
AntiTopaz.lha (from Aminet) and set it to use a font such as topazgr.font
instead of topaz.font .
  Also, you will of course need to set Greek as your preferred language in
Locale Preferences. You may need to download the Boing Bag #2 Greek Locale
package (http://os.amigaworld.de/download.php?id=14) or EPAGrWb.lha (from
Aminet) for eg. the greek.language files.
  You might find this page to be useful:

    http://www.hri.org/culture97/fonts.html#amiga
@endnode

@node Controls "Controls"

Note that the 'Message Delay' slider doesn't affect the "Round # of #"
prompts (because they provide a unique opportunity to restart and/or save
the game), or any prompt which requires a user response.

Be aware that there is a menu which contains important functionality (even
if the titlebar is not being displayed). Since the right mousebutton is
used during the game, you need to move the pointer to the top of the screen
before pressing it, if you want to access the menus.

When finished reading an informational message, pressing RETURN or the
spacebar will continue the game. You can hold down the key to skip
multiple messages.

You can load and play a previously saved game from the title screen (or
CLI). You can save the current game, and/or restart the game, at the start
of each turn. The game is automatically saved (to PROGDIR:Autosave.africa)
at the start of each turn. We suggest using an extension of ".africa" for
saved game files.

The game is played with a combination of mouse and keyboard input.
Counters and hexes are selected with the mouse. Numeric amounts require a
response from the keyboard. Most other things can be done with either
device. You can use the left mouse button for "Yes" and the right mouse
button for "No" and "Esc" (except that you cannot use the right mouse
button for quitting the game).

Information about the hex currently under the pointer is displayed as you
move the mouse around the board. To get detailed information about a
particular hex, press Help when the pointer is over the desired hex.

To find out about declared wars you need to use the appropriate menu item
(Help|Declared Wars...). In the declared wars window, white means "at
war", black means "not applicable", and other colours mean "at peace".

When you are moving, dots indicate possible legal moves. Dots in an enemy
Zone of Control are white (moving into these will end your move); other
dots are black. You are able to undo your most recent move by pressing the
Backspace key.

When you are choosing attacks, the counter borders of possible legal
victim armies will change to white.

Note that using colonial names does not change the counters (ie. flags and
names on the counters will not change).

The 'Watch Amiga movements?' options controls whether you see each
individual move made by Amiga-controlled armies.

Rebel-held cities are dusted with the colour of the rebels.

At the bottom right corner of the screen, you can see the current purposes
of the left and right mouse buttons.
@endnode

